<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Extrabugdetary Progamme</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER>
<A HREF="/tecatom.html">
<IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/worldatom/images/talogo.gif" ALT="IAEA TecAtom"></A>
<P>
<H2>Extrabudgetary Programme on the Safety of WWER and RBMK Nuclear Power Plants</H2>
</center>
<p>
<HR SIZE=3>
Welcome to the pages about the IAEA's safety programme for <A HREF="wwer.html">WWER</A> and <A HREF="rbmk.html">RBMK</A> 
nuclear power plants. The Agency established the programme in 1990 to assist countries of Eastern Europe and the former 
Soviet Union to improve the safety of their first-generation WWER plants (WWER-440/230s). The scope of the programme was 
extended in 1992 to include RBMK, WWER-440/213 and WWER-1000 plants. Click here for a recent 
<A HREF="http://www.iaea.or.at/GC/gc40/documents/gc40inf5ac-2.html">overview of the programme</A> submitted to the IAEA 
General Conference.
<HR SIZE=3>
<P>
<STRONG>
Programme objectives: 
</STRONG>
<P>
<UL>
<LI>to identify major design and operational safety issues;
<LI>to establish an international consensus on priority safety improvements;
<LI>to provide assistance in the review of the completeness and adequacy of safety improvement programmes.
</UL>
<P>
<STRONG>
Programme scope and direction:
</STRONG>
<P>
<DL>
<DD>The programme covers <A HREF="reactors.html">58 operational units and 13 units under construction</A> in seven countries. It is conducted within the Safety Assessment Section of the Division of Nuclear Safety of the IAEA.  The programme has a staff of 14 professional and six secretaries.
</DL>
<P>
More than <A HREF="publications.html">100 documents</A> have been published covering techical missions, safety guidelines, and reactor systems and features.
<P>
A <A HREF="wwersc.html">WWER Steering Committee</A> and a <A HREF="rbmksc.html">RBMK Steering Committee</A> oversees the project.
<P>
<CENTER>
