<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Nuclear techniques and the IAEA - Fact Sheet
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="ltblubar.gif" LINK="#00A8A8" VLINK="#5C3317">
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<CENTER>
<H2>Nuclear techniques and the IAEA</H2>
<SMALL><B>
<A HREF="#note_a">Soil fertility</A> | 
<A HREF="#note_b">Plant breeding</A> | 
<A HREF="#note_c">Animal production</A> |
<A HREF="#note_d">Insect control</A> | 
<A HREF="#note_e">Agrochemicals</A> | 
<A HREF="#note_f">Food preservation</A> | 
<A HREF="#note_g">Nuclear medicine</A> | 
<A HREF="#note_h">Radiation biology</A> | 
<A HREF="#note_i">Radiation dosimetry</A> | 
<A HREF="#note_j">Nutrition</A> |
<A HREF="#note_k">Research reactor</A> | 
<A HREF="#note_l">Industrial applications</A> | 
<A HREF="#note_m">Development of water resources</A>
</B></SMALL></CENTER>
<HR NOSHADE>
<FONT SIZE=+2><B>T</B></FONT>he International Atomic Energy
Agency (IAEA) and its Member
States support hundreds of development projects involving nuclear
science and technology. Technical experts are sent to research
centres and laboratories as advisers or lecturers; group and
individual training is conducted in conjunction with national and
regional host institutes; and equipment is supplied for research
and technical projects in the field.
<P>         
Through these and other avenues, the tools, skills, and
experience that are vital for the safe development of nuclear
energy and science are transferred to where they are needed.
<P>       
Using the IAEA as a base for technical co-operation, many
countries are harvesting the benefits of nuclear energy for their
development. The Agency provides assistance in numerous fields
where nuclear techniques offer advantages over others or can
usefully supplement them.
<P>         
Some activities relate to the generation of electricity by
nuclear reactors. However, the scope of the technical
co-operation programme is much broader, encompassing fields such
as health, agriculture, industry, hydrology, radiation
protection, environmental monitoring, and energy--all areas that
are especially relevant to developing countries.
<P>         
The primary objective of IAEA technical co-operation is to assist
Member States in achieving self-reliance in nuclear science and
technology by strengthening human resources and institutions.
<P>         
The greatest challenge facing many of the IAEA Member States is
the adequate supply of food. Careful husbanding of water and
soil, together with the use of state-of-the-art techniques to get
the most out of natural resources, while still maintaining a
healthy environment, are essential for their economic and social
development.
<P>         
Nuclear techniques are used to help meet these challenges, and
the IAEA technical co-operation programme seeks to assure that
they are available to its Member States. Techniques using
radiation and isotopes are used to improve crop and animal      
production in areas such as soil fertility, plant breeding,
animal health, insect and pest control, pesticide use, and food
preservation.
<P>         
Much work is carried out by the Agency together with the Food and
Agriculture Organization (FAO) through the Joint FAO/IAEA
Division of nuclear techniques in food and agriculture. Founded
in 1964, the division works to solve practical problems related
to agricultural production and food protection in the developing
world.
<A NAME="note_a">
<H3>        
Soil fertility, irrigation, and crop production</A>
</H3>

Nitrogen fertilizers are used widely to increase agricultural
production. Many fertilizers harm the environment and lead to
pollution of water supplies if they are used excessively or
inappropriately. A nuclear technique, which uses a stable
nitrogen isotope as a tracer, helps determine the best form,
timing, and placement of fertilizers to avoid waste and to reduce
its movement in the environment. Others are used to detect,
measure, and track fertilizer supplied nutrients in soil and
plants, determine the availability of soil moisture, and study
the natural process of nitrogen fixation by certain plants, thus
considerably reducing fertilizer costs, while increasing plant
protein.
<P>         
Sustainable agricultural production requires an adequate supply
of water in soils. Work in this area helps irrigation specialists
and others to choose the most appropriate option that will
increase or improve the way water resources are used. Results of
co-ordinated research programmes where neutron moisture gauges
are used extensively show that traditional irrigation methods
can be improved to cut total water use by 40%. Water can thus be
diverted to irrigate additional areas. Different practices to
increase water conservation in rainfed areas have been tested
that have resulted in immediate practical application.
<A NAME="note_b">
<H3>Plant breeding and genetics</H3></A>
Nuclear techniques--sometimes in combination with other
biotechnology--can be used to develop new strains of important
food crops. These techniques have yielded new varieties of many
different crop species, such as rice, wheat, and soybean. Such
varieties may have a better resistance to disease, be of a
higher product quality, or have a higher yield. Worldwide, more
than 1500 mutant cultivars of crop plants and ornamental plants
have been released to growers in the past 30 years. Eight percent
of agricultural land in China, for example, is planted with
mutants of rice, wheat, com, and cotton.
<P>         
The Agency provides assistance to Member States in the proper
application of mutation breeding techniques in highly diversified
plant breeding programmes. Research contracts and agreements
focus on the advancement of mutation breeding technology
particularly to improve root and tuber crops, oil seed crops, and
cereals, and to improve resistance to disease.
<A NAME="note_c">
<H3>Animal production and health</H3></A>
         
Sensitive techniques based on the use of radioactive "tracers"
are used to examine methods of improving animal production and
health. Such techniques are used in studies of cattle, buffalo,
sheep, and goat reproduction in developing countries. For
example, the Agency carries out work on the productivity of
domestic buffalo in Asia and on sheep and goats in Africa and
Asia. Similar methods are used to determine whether animals are
infected with disease-causing agents, an approach which is now
being used widely in veterinary centres in many parts of the
world to diagnose debilitating diseases and monitor control
methods.
<P>         
Co-ordinated research programmes are carried out on the
development of feeding strategies for livestock in areas where
the availability and quality of feed fluctuates greatly between
seasons; the use of nuclear techniques to improve the
reproductive efficiency and diagnosis of diseases in Asian
livestock; seromonitoring of rinderpest vaccination in Africa;
improved methods for diagnosing animal diseases in Latin America;
and improved methods to diagnose and control trypanosomiasis in
cattle and camels in Africa.
<P>         
To make these techniques easier to use in the field, the Agency
produces standardized kits in its laboratory in Seibersdorf and
distributes them worldwide. For example, under the Pan-African
Rinderpest Campaign, appropriate kits are sent regularly to l7
African countries so that veterinarians can monitor accurately
the progress of their vaccination programmes. Additionally, more
than 500 000 assay units for progesterone determination are sent
to animal production research institutes to assist in the
assessment of the reproductive status of livestock species and
hence improve breeding programmes.
<A NAME="note_d">
<H3>Insect and pest control</H3></A>
         
Radiation can be used to sexually sterilize insects. When insects
that are mass-reared and sterilized in laboratories are released
in the wild population, the female mates of sterilized males will
not produce offspring. This method, called the Sterile Insect
Technique (SIT), has been used successfully to control or
eradicate dangerous insects and pests which account for
substantial losses in food supplies and animal production.
<P>         
The technique has been further developed al the IAEA's
Seibersdorf Laboratories. Mass rearing facilities for fruit flies
and tsetse flies using methods developed at the Laboratories,
have been built in a number of countries. The most successful SIT
campaign eradicated the New World Screwworm from the southern
United States, most of Mexico, as well as the islands of Puerto
Rico and Cura&ccedil;ao. The successful eradication is saving
livestock owners more than US$ 378 million each year in the USA
alone. The SIT will be the eradication component in the recently
initiated New World Screwworm Eradication Programme in North
Africa. It also has been used in projects to successfully
eradicate the Mediterranean fruitfly in Mexico and against
various species of tsetse fly in Nigeria.
<A NAME="note_e">

<H3>Agrochemicals and residues</H3></A>
        
The controlled release overtime of active pesticide compounds can
reduce the quantities used by farmers, and thus minimize damage
to the ecosystem. Labelling techniques using radioactive atoms
are a key area of research in agrochemicals and residues. These
techniques track the residues of pesticides in the environment
and greatly facilitate research on studying controlled release of
pesticides. Ecosystems receiving attention are the rice-fish
systems, and the control of tsetse flies through the deployment
of screens and targets treated with pesticides.
<A NAME="note_f">
<H3>Food preservation</H3></A>
         
Member States continue to show interest in food irradiation, a
preservation method increasingly being used along with
traditional ones. It is a physical means of food treatment
comparable to processing food by heating or freezing. Foodstuffs
are exposed to controlled amounts of radiation to delay spoilage,
or to kill insect eggs or micro-organisms which contaminate food.
No radioactivity is induced in the items.
<P>         
Agency activities have focussed on investigating the application
of food irradiation as one way to ensure a safe and adequate food
supply, as well as a plant quarantine treatment to promote
international trade in agricultural products and to transfer the
technology under strict control. Decades of research have shown
conclusively that there are no adverse effects from the
consumption of irradiated foods and that food irradiation is a
safe and effective preservation technique when used under
controlled conditions at licensed facilities. International
efforts have centered on possible uniform regulation of
irradiated foods and to establish an international label to
identify foods that have been irradiated.
<P>         
At the end of 1989, the number of countries where one or more
irradiated food items had been approved for human consumption
totalled 37; of these, 24 countries are using commercial or
demonstration irradiators to process several food items for
commercial purposes.
<A NAME="note_g">
<H3>Nuclear medicine</H3></A>
         
Nuclear techniques are used in a variety of ways in medical
fields. The use of X-rays as a diagnostic aid is well known, but
a wide spectrum of other techniques is available to physicians as
well. It has been estimated that about one fourth of all hospital
patients in the Western industrialized world benefit from the
use of nuclear medicine.
<P>         
Chemical compounds "labelled" with short-lived radioactive
isotopes are especially useful for diagnostic purposes. The
compounds are "watched" as they travel through the organ being
studied to assess how well the organ is functioning. Another
class of diagnostic techniques, in which biological samples taken
from patients are studied using radiochemicals in the laboratory,
reduce risk even further. Such techniques are used to assess
organ functioning by measuring hormone levels, certain proteins
associated with virus infections, and in evaluating the effects
of drug treatments.
<P>         
Within the framework of the IAEA's regional co-operative
agreement for Asia and the Pacific (RCA), a programme to promote
the production and use of bulk reagents for radioimmunoassay has
reduced significantly the cost of the assays of thyroid-related
hormones. A similar programme has been introduced in Latin
America.
<A NAME="note_h">
<H3>Radiation biology and radiotherapy</H3></A>
         
In many countries, doctors use sterile medical care supplies,
such as hypodermic syringes and needles, that are thrown away
after only one clinical use. This is perhaps the most visible
product of the growing use of the microbicidal effects of
radiation to sterilize prepacked medical supplies. A wide variety
of other materials are also sterilized in this way. To improve
quality control of sterility, scientists collaborating in an IAEA
co-ordinated research programme in the Asia and Pacific region
have developed a set of technical procedures. The  Agency has
developed a code of practice for the radiation sterilization of
disposable medical supplies.
<P>         
Radiation also is used for cancer treatment. A variety of
techniques has been developed which is especially useful in
developing countries, where hospital resources are often
limited. One particularly successful development concerns a
technique for the treatment of cervical cancer, which is
prevalent in many developing countries. The Agency and the
World Health Organization (WHO), with the Government of Italy,
are supporting work in Egypt which is saving hundreds of lives
each year.
<A NAME="note_i">
<H3>Radiation dosimetry</H3></A>
        
One out of every three cancer patients receive radiation
treatments. The dose of radiation each patient receives must be
precise. Accurate dosimetry--the measurement of radiation
doses--is a key IAEA field of concern. The Agency and
participating institutes in Member States have established a
network of Secondary Standard Dosimetry Laboratories (SSDLs) to
expand the number of laboratories that can maintain accurate
standard measurement instruments. National laboratories
participating in the SSDL network can determine the accuracy of
their own instruments and check instruments used in the field.
For countries without an operational SSDL, the IAEA's dosimetry
laboratory at Seibersdorf provides calibration services upon
request.
<P>         
To assist users of radiotherapy equipment, the Agency and WHO
operate a"postal dose intercomparison service". Hospitals using
this service receive dosimeters whose accuracy is known, and are
requested to expose them to what their instruments tell them is a
certain calculated dose. The dosimeters are returned to Vienna
for checking, and the hospitals told the results so that they can
check their instruments. Some 340 hospitals make use of this
service, most of them repeatedly.
<A NAME="note_j">
<H3>Nutrition and health</H3></A>
         
Nuclear techniques are used widely in studies of the body's need
for, and use of, trace elements; and in ways in which we are
affected by pollution in the environment. The Agency's
 work in this area is largely centered on co-ordinating work in
the field, and in providing advice and training. It also supports
work in Member Slates by making available certified reference
materials against which workers studying human nutrition and
environmental pollution can check their measurements. Programmes
are conducted in areas where nuclear techniques are used in
analyses of toxic elements in foodstuffs and in the study of
environmental pollution associated with solid wastes.
<A NAME="note_k">
<H3>Research reactor support</H3></A>
         
Nuclear power is used for electricity generation in only certain
countries, but many others use research reactors as a training
tool, for pure research, to support analytical techniques, and
for the production of radioisotopes used in industry,
agriculture, and medicine.
<P>         
Today there are 325 research reactors operating in 54 Member
States, including 71 in 34 developing countries. The Agency's
programme is aimed at converting some research reactors from the
use of high-enriched uranium fuels, which are limited, to
low-enriched fuels. It also seeks to enhance the use of these
reactors to serve multiple purposes in areas of research and
practical applications.
<A NAME="note_l">
<H3>Industrial applications</H3></A>
         
Many beneficial applications of radiation and radioisotopes are
now well established in industry in advanced countries. Main
areas of application include activities in radiography,
non-destructive testing, radiation engineering and technology,
control systems and radioactive tracers, analytical techniques
and quality control, borehole logging and rock characterization,
and the production of radioactively-labelled pharmaceuticals,
including necessary quality control techniques and procedures for
their safe use.
<P>         
For example, radiotracer applications in the chemical, oil
production and refining, steel, cement, automotive, and maritime
industries have offered considerable economic benefits and have
provided solutions to problems which could not be solved by other
techniques.
<A NAME="note_m">
<H3>Development of water and mineral resources</H3></A>
         
Techniques using "environmental" isotopes are among those that
meteorologists hydrologists, and hydrogeologists use in the study
of water. Study of the isotopes of oxygen and hydrogen in water,
and of elements contained in dissolved salts which have the same
behaviour as water, enables exact recording of phenomena
affecting the occurrence and movement of water in all its forms
(ice, gas, or liquid).
<P>         
In the Amazon Basin, for example, such techniques play a key role
in investigating the  environmental consequences of the clearing
of tropical rain forests. Stable isotopes are providing data on
vapour movements, stream flow, sedimentation, water quality,
plant protection and soil changes. Ultimately these studies
should have decisive impact on the ecological management of the
region.
<HR NOSHADE>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
</BODY>
</HTML>         


</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT19-B36-86</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA029-000313-B044-233</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
