<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Working at the IAEA
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<CENTER>
<H3>
Working at the IAEA
</H3>
</CENTER>
<P>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
The IAEA is the world's central intergovernmental forum for
co-operation in the peaceful uses of nuclear energy.  Its
mission, as stated in its <A HREF="/worldatom/glance/profile/statute.html">Statute</A>, is to assist
governments in ensuring the safe and peaceful global development
of nuclear energy and related technologies.  
<P>
To carry out its mission, the Agency is headed by a <A HREF="/worldatom/glance/profile/blixcv.htm">Director General</A> and
organizationally structured into <A HREF="/worldatom/glance/profile/#item2">six Departments</A>, each headed by a Deputy Director General.  Its <A HREF="/worldatom/glance/policy/">policymaking organs</A> of Member States are the General Conference and the 35-member IAEA Board of
Governors.  
<P>
All told, the IAEA has about 2000 staff members from more than 80
countries with expertise in a variety of scientific, technical,
managerial, and professional disciplines.  Most of these men and
women work at Agency headquarters in Vienna, Austria, with others
working at IAEA field offices in Toronto and Tokyo, liaison
offices in New York and Geneva, and <A HREF="/worldatom/laboratory/index.html">research laboratories</A> in Seibersdorf, Austria, and in Monaco.
<P>
Staff members are international civil servants subject to the
authority of the Director General.  As such, they  may not seek
or accept instructions in regard to the performance of their
duties from any government or other authority external to the
Agency.   While all staff members are subject to the laws and
regulations of the duty station country, they are entitled to
certain privileges and immunities in the interests of the IAEA. 
These include immunity from legal process in respect of words
spoken or written, and of acts performed in line with official
duties; immunity from seizure of personal and official baggage;
exemption from taxation in respect of salaries paid by the IAEA;
and exemption from immigration restrictions and alien
registration.  
<P>
For professional positions, the IAEA follows a policy of
rotation.  This means that appointments typically are for an
initial three-year period with no expectation or right to
extension, renewal, or conversion to another type of appointment.

Based on programme requirements and work performance, the Agency
may offer an extension for a period of two years, bringing the
total service to five years.  As a rule, five years constitute
the maximum period a staff member can expect to be employed by
the IAEA.
<P>
In terms of language backgrounds and skills, IAEA staff typically
are multi-lingual.  Agency business is usually conducted in
English, but knowlege of other official languages (Arabic,
Chinese, French, Russian, or Spanish) is an advantage.  At Agency
headquarters in Vienna, knowledge of German is an additional
asset, both for working contacts and for life outside of office
hours.
<P>
Detailed information about employment opportunities at the IAEA
may be obtained by writing to the Recruitment Unit, Division of
Personnel, IAEA, P.O. Box 100, A-1400 Vienna, Austria.
<P>
<A NAME="apply">
<HR SIZE=1 NOSHADE>
<P>
<CENTER>
<H3>How to Apply for Posts</H3>
</CENTER></A>
<P>
Interested applicants may inquire about employment opportunities
at the IAEA at any time.  To be assured of consideration for a
specific position, however, they must apply in writing following
the issuance of an official Vacancy Notice.  Applications must be
received before the Closing Date as stated on the Vacancy Notice
itself.  (The Personal History Form accessible here can be printed out and used for the application
process; it may not be transmitted to the IAEA electronically, however.) 
<P>
Vacancy Notices are issued months before a position becomes
available at the Agency.  As a matter of routine, they are now
accessible over the Internet at the IAEA's main address (<A HREF="http://www.iaea.or.at">http://www.iaea.or.at</A>).  Copies
of announcements also are sent to all Member States, typically to
the Atomic Energy Commissions, Ministries of Foreign Affairs,
other international organizations, universities and other
educational institutions.  Abridged forms of the announcements
are published in the <I>IAEA Bulletin</I>, the Agency's quarterly
journal.  
<P>
In a cover letter, applicants should state their nationality and
quote the number of the Vacancy Notice for which they are
applying.  Applications should be sent to the Division of
Personnel, IAEA, Wagramerstrasse 5, P.O. Box 100, A-1400 Vienna,
Austria.  Applicants will be informed of the outcome of the
evaluation process approximately two months after the Closing
Date. 
<P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR NOSHADE SIZE=1>
<P>
<CENTER>
Download the IAEA Personal History Form <A HREF="ftp://ftp.iaea.or.at/pub/vacancy_posts/phf.zip">(phf.zip)</A>.
<P>
</CENTER>
